<TITLE> Spain needs new financial control body, says minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MADRID, June 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Spain needs a new financial control body with powers of relegation to stop its soccer clubs spending more than they earn, the sports minister was quoted as saying on Monday. Spain has no mechanism to punish insolvent clubs and secretary of state for sport Jaime Lissavetzky said a commission including representatives from soccer organisations and the government was needed to enforce a clearer set of rules. "(The clubs') lack of solvency and the existence of massive debts is worrying and the time has come to fix the situation," he told As newspaper, without setting a timeframe. "There is no coercive mechanism such as this independent and public financial control body could be. It would set some clear rules under which anyone that broke them would be relegated, without exception." A recent study by an accounting professor at the University of Barcelona showed the combined debt of the 20 clubs in Spain's top division swelled by more than 650 million euros to at least 3.5 billion ($4.85 billion) in the year through June 2008. Lissavetzky said he favoured a rule preventing clubs spending more than 60 percent of their budget on wages
